      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "title: \"Lecture 3: Dimension Reduction\"\n",
        "subtitle: \"Finding Structure in High-Dimensional Data\"\n",
        "date: \"Day 2, 9:00–10:00\"\n",
        "format:\n",
        "  revealjs:\n",
        "    theme: default\n",
        "    slide-number: true\n",
        "    chalkboard: true\n",
        "    smaller: true\n",
        "    scrollable: true\n",
        "    code-fold: true\n",
        "    footer: \"High-Dimensional Data Analysis Workshop | BTP\"\n",
        "    math: mathjax\n",
        "jupyter: python3\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# The Eigenface That Launched a Thousand Papers {.centered}\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## From Faces to Genes\n",
        "\n",
        "In 1991, Turk and Pentland ran PCA on a database of face photographs. The principal components — ghostly, blurred images they called **\"eigenfaces\"** — could reconstruct any face in the database using just 100 numbers instead of thousands of pixels.\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "This was the moment dimension reduction went from mathematical abstraction to transformative tool: a high-dimensional object (a face) could be faithfully represented in a far lower-dimensional space.\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "The same idea now drives single-cell genomics, where 30,000 gene measurements per cell are routinely compressed to 30–50 principal components before any analysis.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Problem\n",
        "\n",
        "We have data $X \\in \\mathbb{R}^{n \\times p}$ with $p$ large (thousands to tens of thousands).\n",
        "\n",
        "**Goals**:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Visualization**: Project to 2D or 3D for exploration\n",
        "- **Denoising**: Separate signal from noise\n",
        "- **Preprocessing**: Reduce $p$ before applying downstream methods (clustering, regression)\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "**Core question**: Can we represent the data in a lower-dimensional space $\\mathbb{R}^k$ with $k \\ll p$, preserving the important structure?\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Principal Component Analysis (PCA)\n",
        "\n",
        "### The idea\n",
        "\n",
        "Find orthogonal directions of maximum variance in the data.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Formally\n",
        "\n",
        "Given centered data $X$ ($n \\times p$), PCA solves:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\mathbf{v}_1 = \\arg\\max_{\\|\\mathbf{v}\\| = 1} \\text{Var}(X\\mathbf{v}) = \\arg\\max_{\\|\\mathbf{v}\\| = 1} \\mathbf{v}^T \\hat{\\Sigma} \\mathbf{v}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The solution $\\mathbf{v}_1$ is the eigenvector of $\\hat{\\Sigma} = \\frac{1}{n-1}X^TX$ with the largest eigenvalue.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## PCA via the SVD\n",
        "\n",
        "The **singular value decomposition** of $X$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$X = U D V^T$$\n",
        "\n",
        "- $U$ ($n \\times r$): left singular vectors (sample directions)\n",
        "- $D$ ($r \\times r$): diagonal matrix of singular values $d_1 \\geq d_2 \\geq \\cdots \\geq 0$\n",
        "- $V$ ($p \\times r$): right singular vectors (loadings = principal component directions)\n",
        "\n",
        "where $r = \\min(n, p)$. Software returns this \"thin\" SVD by default.\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "**Connection**: Eigenvalues of $\\hat{\\Sigma}$ are $\\lambda_j = d_j^2 / (n-1)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "**PC scores**: $Z = XV = UD$ (the $j$-th column of $Z$ is the $j$-th principal component).\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## How Many Components?\n",
        "\n",
        "### Scree plot\n",
        "\n",
        "Plot $\\lambda_j$ (or proportion of variance explained) vs. $j$. Look for an \"elbow.\"\n",
        "\n",
        "### Proportion of variance explained\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\text{PVE}(k) = \\frac{\\sum_{j=1}^k \\lambda_j}{\\sum_{j=1}^p \\lambda_j}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "### Formal methods\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Marchenko–Pastur threshold**: Under null ($\\Sigma = I$) with $\\gamma = p/n$, eigenvalues lie in $[\\max(0,\\,(1-\\sqrt{\\gamma})^2),\\; (1+\\sqrt{\\gamma})^2]$. When $p > n$ (our regime), the lower edge is 0 and only the upper edge matters. Eigenvalues above $(1+\\sqrt{\\gamma})^2$ are signal.\n",
        "- **Parallel analysis**: Compare observed eigenvalues to those from permuted data.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## PCA: Strengths and Limitations\n",
        "\n",
        "### Strengths\n",
        "\n",
        "- Computationally fast; solved by standard linear algebra\n",
        "- Optimal for linear reconstruction (Eckart–Young theorem)\n",
        "- Interpretable loadings: which variables contribute to each PC?\n",
        "\n",
        "### Limitations\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Linear only**: Cannot capture nonlinear manifold structure\n",
        "- **Sensitive to scaling**: Must standardize or choose units carefully\n",
        "- **Rotation ambiguity**: PCs are identified only up to sign\n",
        "- **High-D noise bias**: In the $p \\gg n$ regime, the Marchenko–Pastur law inflates eigenvalues. Leading PCs can be distorted.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Biplots\n",
        "\n",
        "A biplot overlays sample scores and variable loadings on the same 2D plot."
      ],
      "id": "c03d4fcd"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-height": 5
      },
      "source": [
        "#| echo: true\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "from sklearn.decomposition import PCA\n",
        "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n",
        "from sklearn.datasets import load_iris\n",
        "\n",
        "iris = load_iris()\n",
        "X_iris = StandardScaler().fit_transform(iris.data)\n",
        "pca_iris = PCA(n_components=2).fit(X_iris)\n",
        "scores = pca_iris.transform(X_iris)\n",
        "loadings = pca_iris.components_.T  # (4, 2)\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7, 5))\n",
        "ax.scatter(scores[:, 0], scores[:, 1], s=15, color=\"gray\", alpha=0.6)\n",
        "scale = np.abs(scores).max() / np.abs(loadings).max() * 0.8\n",
        "for i, name in enumerate(iris.feature_names):\n",
        "    ax.arrow(0, 0, loadings[i, 0] * scale, loadings[i, 1] * scale,\n",
        "             color=\"red\", head_width=0.1, linewidth=1.5)\n",
        "    ax.text(loadings[i, 0] * scale * 1.15, loadings[i, 1] * scale * 1.15,\n",
        "            name, color=\"red\", fontsize=9, ha=\"center\")\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel(f\"PC1 ({pca_iris.explained_variance_ratio_[0]:.1%})\")\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel(f\"PC2 ({pca_iris.explained_variance_ratio_[1]:.1%})\")\n",
        "ax.set_title(\"Biplot of Iris Data\")\n",
        "ax.axhline(0, color=\"gray\", linewidth=0.5)\n",
        "ax.axvline(0, color=\"gray\", linewidth=0.5)\n",
        "plt.tight_layout()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "930a29b6",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
